Prosper loans project

by Michał Kaszuba

This project was created during Data Analyst Nanodegree by Udacity Visit Udacity Data set was downloaded form Udacity site

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

I will try to anwser following questions:

Are people who own property are more willing to take loans?

Is specific occupations are more willing to take loans, and which one has the highest debts (Income to debt ratio)?

What affects the borrower’s APR or interest rate?

We will be only intrested in few columns for further analysis:

ListingKey : Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.

Term : The length of the loan expressed in months.

BorrowerAPR : The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

BorrowerRate : The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.

ProsperScore : A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009

Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.

IsBorrowerHomeowner : A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.

DebtToIncomeRatio: The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).

Now when We know what We want. Let's create dataset this way

Bivariate Exploration

In [6]:
occupationsmean = loans.groupby('Occupation').mean()
In [11]:
def plotThisbar(data,title,ylabel,color):
    '''To save time we will use this function with set size,kind,and grid'''
    data.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(18,5),title=title,color=color, ylabel=ylabel,grid=True);

What was the average Debt to Income ratio for each occupation?

In [9]:
plotThisbar(occupationsmean['DebtToIncomeRatio'],'Average debt to income ratio for occupations','Debt to income ratio','pink')

Most borrowers have a debt to income ratio between 0.2 and 0.3. Teacher's Aides are willing to spend over 45% of their salaries for loan installments. Students as a group tends to have very high income to debt ratio except for the ones in technical schools which have the lowest average debt to income ratio among dataset.

Let's check the average borrowers ARP among diffrent occupations.

In [14]:
plotThisbar(occupationsmean['BorrowerAPR'],'Average borrower ARP for occupations','Borrower ARP','lavender')

Most borrowers have ARP between 20% and 25%. Homemakers have the highest average ARP among occupations. Teacher's Aides have very high average ARP and Students in Technical schools lowest. We may expect that Income to Debt Ratio has some influence on borrowers ARP since most of the occupations with higher debt to income ratio has higher ARP as well.

What was the average Prosper Score for each occupation?

In [13]:
plotThisbar(occupationsmean['ProsperScore'],'Average Prosper Score for occupations','Prosper Score','forestgreen')

And here We got opposite. Occupations that previously had lower ARP has a higher Prosper Score.

plt.title('Borrowers ARP for diffrent prosper scores in relation to owning a property')
plt.ylabel('Borrower ARP')
plt.xlabel('Prosper Score');

Having a property seems to have no effect on borrowers ARP, no matter what prosper score the borrower has.

Conclusions

What affect Borrowers ARP the most is Prosper Score. Different occupations get different Prosper Scores of average. Owning a property does not affect our loan ARP or Prosper Score much. Term of loan sometimes could have effect on loan. Peoples with high Prosper Scores got lower Debt to Income Ratio on average.
